multiplesheets <- function(fname) {
   
  # getting info about all excel sheets
  sheets <- readxl::excel_sheets(fname)
  tibble <- lapply(sheets, function(x) readxl::read_excel(fname, sheet = x))
  data_frame <- lapply(tibble, as.data.frame)
    
  # assigning names to data frames
  names(data_frame) <- sheets
    
  # print data frame
  print(data_frame)
}

# Annual output per hour worked 
g7_prod <- raw_world_g7$Table_9 %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  row_to_names(row_number = 1) %>% 
  clean_names() %>% 
  pivot_longer(!year, names_to = "country", values_to = "productivity") %>% 
  mutate(productivity = round(as.numeric(productivity), digits = 2),
         country = str_to_title(country))

g7_prod_avg <- g7_prod %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(productivity = round(mean(productivity), digits = 2))

g7_prod %>% 
  filter(country == "Uk") %>% 
  ggplot()+
  aes(x = year, y = productivity, group = country, colour = "brown2")+
  geom_point()+
  geom_line()+
  geom_line(aes(x = g7_prod_avg$year, y = g7_prod_avg$productivity, group = country), linetype = 2, colour = "black")+
  labs(title = "Productivity in G7 Countries")+
  xlab("Year")+
  ylab("Output Per Hour Worked ()")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45))

G7 - Output Per Hour wored growth

g7_prod_growth <- raw_world_g7$Table_16 %>% 
  na.omit() %>% 
  row_to_names(row_number = 1) %>% 
  clean_names()%>% 
  mutate(across(c(2:8), as.numeric)) %>% 
  pivot_longer(!year, names_to = "country", values_to = "growth_rate")


g7_avg_prod_growth <- g7_prod_growth%>% 
  filter(country != "uk") %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(g7_avg = mean(growth_rate))%>% 
   mutate(
    moving_avg = slide_dbl(
      .x = g7_avg,
      .f = ~mean(.,na.rm = TRUE),
# 2 weeks moving average
      .before = 2
    )  )


g7_prod_growth %>% 
  filter(country == "uk") %>% 
   mutate(
    moving_avg = slide_dbl(
      .x = growth_rate,
      .f = ~mean(.,na.rm = TRUE),
      # 2 weeks moving average
      .before = 2
                        )) %>% 
  ggplot()+
  aes(x = year, y = moving_avg, group = country, colour = country)+
  geom_point()+
  geom_line()+
  geom_line(aes(x = g7_avg_prod_growth$year, y = g7_avg_prod_growth$moving_avg, group = country, colour = country), linetype = 2, colour = "black")+
  labs(title = "2 Years Moving Average Grow Rate comparison between UK and Other G7 Countries")+
  xlab("Year")+
  ylab("Growth Rate Per year (%)")+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45))

uk_france_diff_prod <- g7_prod %>% 
  filter(country %in% c("Uk", "France")) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = country, values_from = productivity) %>% 
  mutate(diff_in_prod = (France / Uk)-1)

uk_france_diff_gva <- oecd_gva_g7 %>% 
    filter(country %in% c("United Kingdom", "France")) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = country, values_from = gva) %>% 
  rename(Uk = 'United Kingdom') %>% 
  mutate(diff_in_gva = (France / Uk)-1)

Note: Among all the G7 countries, We will be using France as a comparison and find out factors that we can increase productivity in. France has a similar size in terms of the country and population. In the graph of difference in GVA and Productivity, you can see from the red line, GVA, that France has a lower GVA (net output) when compared to the UK, and yet the productivity gap is increasing since 2008 and onwards. In this comparison, we can reduce any confounding variables

# GVA Per Hour Worked in 
clean_pro_indu_gvaph <- raw_pro_indu$`GVA CP` %>% 
  # Remove redundant columns
  slice(-c(1,2,3,5)) %>% 
  row_to_names(row_number = 1) %>% 
  rename(year = "SIC07:") %>% 
  pivot_longer(!year, names_to = "sic07", values_to = "oph") %>% 
  mutate(oph = round(as.numeric(oph), digits = 2)) %>% 
  left_join(sic_identify, by = "sic07") %>% 
  select(-c("sic07", "description")) %>% 
  relocate(cat, .before = "oph") %>% 
  separate(year, c("year", "quarter"), " ") %>% 
  group_by(year, cat) %>% 
  summarise(oph = round(mean(oph), digits = 2)) %>% 
  mutate(show_we = case_when(
                    cat == "WE" ~ TRUE,
                    TRUE ~ FALSE))
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'year'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
  
clean_pro_indu_gvaph_rate <- clean_pro_indu_gvaph %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    group_by(cat) %>% 
  mutate(rate = (oph - lag(oph))/lag(oph))
  

clean_pro_indu_gvaph %>%
  filter(cat != "L" & cat != "WE") %>%
  ggplot()+

  row_to_names(row_number = 1) %>% 
  filter(Unit %in% "US Dollar, 2020", Country %in% c("France", "United Kingdom")) %>% 
  select(-Unit) %>% 
  pivot_longer(!1, names_to = "year", values_to = "avg_wage") %>% 
  clean_names()%>% 
  mutate(avg_wage = round(as.numeric(avg_wage), digits = 2))

1  Each data table has metadata in rows 1-5 followed by data with at least 217 columns along with two header rows, and one data row for each year from 1998.  The first header row has merged cells containing names of ITL1 geographies.  The second header row has industry identifiers from the standard industry classification (SIC), and descriptions for each industry.  Most tables include data for the whole of the UK in addition to the ITL1 regions and devolved nations, but these are omitted on the tables 'OpJ (relative)' and 'OpH (relative)'.  The first column of each table identifies the year for each row.
2                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Productivity data (output per job and output per hour) are consistent with the most recent annual regional GDP data available at the time of publication.  Measures of labour input (jobs and hours) are consistent with the most recent quarterly regional productivity hours and jobs (ITL1).
3                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             The 17 industry categories in this dataset span the whole of the UK economy.  They are mutually exclusive except that the aggregate 'G-J & L-T' overlaps services industries other than industry 'K'.
4                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     Gross value added (GVA) and labour measures used in this dataset are allocated to geographic regions on a local unit (LU) basis not a reporting unit (RU) basis, so the data measure where economic activity occurs and not just where the associated head office is located.
5                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              <NA>
6                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          Guidance
7                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    Jobs data show how total employment in the economy was distributed across industries and regions.  Jobs values can be added across industries or regions, and can be averaged over time periods.  Jobs for one industry, or region, or time period can be compared to another.
8                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               Hours data show how the total weekly hours worked in the economy were distributed across industries and regions.  Hours worked values are additive, so can easily be aggregated across industries or regions or time periods.  Hours worked for one industry, or region, or time period can be compared to another.
9                                                                                                                        Output per job (OpJ) values here are current price (CP) data showing how productivity for each industry in each region compared to other cells for a particular time period, not adjusted for inflation.  These data do not show whether real productivity was higher or lower in one time period than another, or whether productivity grew faster in one industry or region than another over time.  OpJ CP values for aggregate industries can be calculated from component industry OpJ and Jobs data.
10                                                                                                                     Output per hour (OpH) values here are current price (CP) data showing how productivity for each industry in each region compared to other cells for a particular time period, not adjusted for inflation.  These data do not show whether real productivity was higher or lower in one time period than another, or whether productivity grew faster in one industry or region than another over time.  OpH CP values for aggregate industries can be calculated from component industry OpH and Hours data.
11                                                                                     Relative output per job (OpJ) values compare current price productivity for each industry in each region to overall UK productivity for that industry for a particular time period.  Values greater than 100 indicate an industry that had productivity higher in the region than in the UK as a whole.  Values less than 100 indicate the opposite.  These data do not show whether productivity was higher or lower in one time period than another, or whether productivity grew faster in one industry or region than another over time.
12                                                                                    Relative output per hour (OpH) values compare current price productivity for each industry in each region to overall UK productivity for that industry for a particular time period.  Values greater than 100 indicate an industry that had productivity higher in the region than in the UK as a whole.  Values less than 100 indicate the opposite.  These data do not show whether productivity was higher or lower in one time period than another, or whether productivity grew faster in one industry or region than another over time.
13                                                                                                                                                     Chained volume metric (CVM) output per job (OpJ) data show how OpJ productivity grew over time in each industry, measured in real prices of the reference year.  Growth rates can be calculated as described below.  OpJ CVM data do not show whether productivity for one industry was higher than another for a particular time period.  CVM values are not additive, so OpJ CVM for aggregate industries cannot be calculated from component industry OpJ and Hours data.
14                                                                                                                                                    Chained volume metric (CVM) output per hour (OpH) data show how OpH productivity grew over time in each industry, measured in real prices of the reference year.  Growth rates can be calculated as described below.  OpH CVM data do not show whether productivity for one industry was higher than another for a particular time period.  CVM values are not additive, so OpH CVM for aggregate industries cannot be calculated from component industry OpH and Hours data.
15                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           To calculate percentage growth compared to the year before, the following sequence of calculations can be applied to OpJ CVM or OpH CVM values to obtain the year-on-year growth rate.
16                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             Divide the target productivity value by the corresponding one from the year before, then subtract 1.
17                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        Alternatively, subtract the initial productivity value from the final one then divide by the initial one.
18                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           Multiply by 100 to express the result as a percentage.
19                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         To calculate an "average" annual growth rate over a multi-year span, the following sequence of calculations can be applied to OpJ CVM or OpH CVM values to obtain the compound annual growth rate.  It is generally not meaningful to calculate a simple average of annual growth rates.
20                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          Divide the final productivity value by the initial one.
21                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      Take the natural logarithm, which is often written as "ln".
22                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 Divide by the number of years between the initial and final productivity values.
23                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         Apply the natural exponential function, which is often written as "exp".
24                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      Subtract 1.
25                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           Multiply by 100 to express the result as a percentage.

  filter(sic %in% "All Industries") %>% 
  group_by(year, countries) %>% 
  summarise(avg_oph = mean(oph)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  group_by(countries) %>% 
  arrange(countries, year) %>% 
  mutate(rate = (avg_oph - lag(avg_oph))/lag(avg_oph)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(
    moving_avg_rate = slide_dbl(

      .f = ~mean(.,na.rm = TRUE),
      # 2 weeks moving average
      .before = 2
                        ))
